"""
The `FgRegister` class provides a set of predefined foreground color styles for use in terminal output, including classic colors and less commonly supported extended colors. Each style is accessible as an attribute of an instance of this class. The available colors include standard black, red, green, yellow, blue, magenta, cyan, light grey, dark grey, lighter shades of the basic colors, and least supported deep shades of these colors.

Attributes:
    black (Style): Style for black foreground color.
    red (Style): Style for red foreground color.
    green (Style): Style for green foreground color.
    yellow (Style): Style for yellow foreground color.
    blue (Style): Style for blue foreground color.
    magenta (Style): Style for magenta foreground color.
    cyan (Style): Style for cyan foreground color.
    li_grey (Style): Style for light grey foreground color.
    da_grey (Style): Style for dark grey foreground color.
    li_red (Style): Style for lighter red foreground color.
    li_green (Style): Style for lighter green foreground color.
    li_yellow (Style): Style for lighter yellow foreground color.
    li_blue (Style): Style for lighter blue foreground color.
    li_magenta (Style): Style for lighter magenta foreground color.
    li_cyan (Style): Style for lighter cyan foreground color.
    white (Style): Style for white foreground color.
    da_black (Style): Style for deep black foreground color.
    da_red (Style): Style for deep red foreground color.
    da_green (Style): Style for deep green foreground color.
    da_yellow (Style): Style for deep yellow foreground color.
    da_blue (Style): Style for deep blue foreground color.
    da_magenta (Style): Style for deep magenta foreground color.
    da_cyan (Style): Style for deep cyan foreground color.
    grey (Style): Style for a mid-tone grey foreground color.
    rs (Style): Reset style to default terminal foreground color.

Examples:
    To use the `FgRegister` class, create an instance and access its attributes for different colors:
    
        fg = FgRegister()
        print(f"{fg.red}Red Text{fg.rs}")  # Prints red text followed by resetting to default color.
        print(f"{fg.green}Green Text{fg.rs}")  # Prints green text followed by resetting to default color.
    
    This allows for easy creation of colored terminal output in scripts and applications.
"""
